Lotononis bainesii

   [1367.jpg]
    Authority   Baker
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Fabales:Leguminosae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 1367

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A herbaceous legume with slender stoloniferous stems,
   irregular branched, up to 1-1.5 m long. Plants form a dense pasture up
   to 60 cm high, or under heavy grazing a more prostrate herbage. Leaves
   smooth, trifoliate with the central leaflet being the larges. Flowers
   are small, yellow, 8-23 together in dense umbrella shaped heads. USES
   Used for pasture and withstands heavy grazing, and it makes a good
   silage. GROWING PERIOD A summer-growing short-lived perennial with
   considerable winter greenness. COMMON NAMES Lotononis, Miles lotononis,
   Creeping indigo, Thua-lotononit. FURTHER INF The species is indigenous
   to South Africa and can be found in the subtropics and in tropical
   highlands areas above 600 m in elevation. It occur naturally between
   latitudes 20 and 34Â°S. Can be found in areas with rainfall as low as
   250 mm per year. Dry matter yields may be between 2-8 t/ha, but in very
   dry years production may practically cease.

